---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../../../components/CodeExample.astro';
import HubCard from '../../../../components/HubCard.astro';

const title = 'Utility-first vs LSCSS';
const description = 'Why utility-first CSS in markup fails semantics and maintainability—and how Layered Semantic CSS keeps styling in architecture, not class soup.';

const utilityMarkupExample = `<section class="grid gap-4 p-4 rounded bg-surface shadow-sm">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Section title</h2>
    <p class="text-sm">Content goes here</p>
</section>`;

const semanticExample = `<section class="feature-panel">
    <h2 class="title">Section title</h2>
    <p class="content">Content goes here</p>
</section>`;

const allowedUtilities = `.vh
.a11y-link
.a11y-link--focusable`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title={title}
    description={description}
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>

        <h1>
            Utility-first vs LSCSS
        </h1>

        <p>
            Utility-first CSS means styling through many small classes in HTML.
            LSCSS means semantic markup, layered CSS, and rare helpers only where
            they are truly universal. This site argues utility-first is bad
            architecture: it is not semantic, it bloats HTML, and it does not
            scale calmly—whatever the speed claims in week one.
        </p>

        <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Utility-first and LSCSS comparison sections">
            <a href="#problems">Problems with utility-first</a>
            <a href="#differences">Differences</a>
            <a href="#markup">Markup</a>
            <a href="#lscss-utilities">LSCSS utilities layer</a>
            <a href="#migrating">Leaving utility-first</a>
        </nav>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="problems">
                Problems with utility-first CSS
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>
                    Presentation and structure are fused—HTML stops describing
                    content and starts describing design tokens inline.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Templates become long, repetitive, and hard to diff meaningfully.
                </li>
                <li>
                    “Reuse” is copy-paste of class strings, not shared component
                    ownership in CSS.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Onboarding means learning a parallel styling language in
                    attributes, not reading the stylesheet.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Global design changes require hunting markup, not updating a
                    component or theme layer.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                Utility-first is often sold as consistency. Consistency of
                <em>class names</em> is not the same as a maintainable system.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="differences">
                Main differences
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>Utility-first: styling decisions live in markup.</li>
                <li>LSCSS: styling decisions live in CSS architecture.</li>
                <li>Utility-first: composition via class stacks on each element.</li>
                <li>LSCSS: components, modifiers, state classes, and theme.</li>
                <li>Utility-first: fast to type, costly to own.</li>
                <li>LSCSS: more discipline up front, calmer later.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="markup">
                Markup comparison
            </h2>

            <CodeExample code={utilityMarkupExample} language="html" />

            <p>
                Every visual choice is visible in the HTML—and that is the problem.
                The page reads like a styling spreadsheet, not a document.
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={semanticExample} language="html" />

            <p>
                The same UI can stay understandable in the template while CSS
                handles layout, spacing, colour, and responsive behaviour.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="lscss-utilities">
                The LSCSS utilities layer is not utility-first
            </h2>

            <p>
                In utility-first systems, utilities <em>are</em> the system. In
                LSCSS, the utilities layer is a small escape hatch:
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={allowedUtilities} />

            <p>
                Accessibility helpers and genuinely universal patterns—not
                margin utilities on every block. If a combination repeats, name a
                component and move on.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="migrating">
                Leaving utility-first behind
            </h2>

            <p>
                You do not have to rewrite everything overnight. Isolate
                utility-heavy markup in a legacy layer, stop adding new utility
                stacks, and promote repeated patterns into components as you touch
                files. See <a href="/apply/migration/">migration</a> and
                <a href="/apply/examples/#utilities">utility overload examples</a>.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Next useful pages
            </h2>

            <div class="hub-grid">
                <HubCard href="/learn/comparisons/tailwind-vs-lscss/" title="Tailwind vs LSCSS">
                <p>The most common utility-first toolchain, named explicitly.</p>
            </HubCard>

                <HubCard href="/apply/utilities/" title="Utilities">
                <p>What helpers are allowed in LSCSS—and what is not.</p>
            </HubCard>

                <HubCard href="/apply/decision-trees/" title="Decision trees">
                <p>Utility or component? The answer is usually component.</p>
            </HubCard>
            </div>
        </section>

        <p>
            Utility-first trades long-term clarity for short-term typing speed.
            LSCSS refuses that trade for documentation sites, content platforms,
            and any front end that has to survive handover.
        </p>
    </article>
</DocsLayout>
